  <h2>Give remotes and chargers one landing place</h2>
  <p>
    Small items become irritating because they move between the sofa, coffee table and TV unit.
    One shallow tray, drawer or box near the usual seat is normally enough for remotes,
    controllers and charging leads.
  </p>
  <p>
    Keep the charging route clear of feet and soft furnishings, do not run cords beneath rugs and
    use electrical products according to their instructions. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-cable-management-what-to-plan-before-buying-organisers/">living room cable management guide</a>{" "}
    covers power boards, devices, lamps and cleaning access in more detail.
  </p>

  <h2>Ask every table to earn its floor space</h2>
  <p>
    A storage coffee table can hide games and chargers, but its lid or drawers need room to open.
    A lift top may be useful for occasional laptop work yet add weight and moving parts. An open
    table makes the room feel lighter but offers nowhere for daily clutter to disappear.
  </p>
  <p>
    Side tables solve a different problem: they provide a close surface for a drink, lamp or
    book. Measure their height against the sofa arm and leave comfortable passage around them.
    Before adding either type, compare the usable surface and clearance in the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/side-tables-coffee-tables-and-console-tables-what-to-compare-before-you-buy/">living room tables guide</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep blankets near the seat, not in the best cupboard</h2>
  <p>
    Throws used most nights need an easy return point. A roomy basket beside the sofa, a storage
    ottoman or one shelf in the TV unit may be more successful than a linen cupboard in another
    room. Store only the number regularly used; extra seasonal bedding can live elsewhere.
  </p>
  <p>
    Make sure an ottoman or bench does not narrow the route through the seating area. If the room
    already feels tight, revisit the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/sofa-and-seating-layout-what-to-measure-before-buying-furniture/">sofa and seating layout guide</a>{" "}
    before adding more furniture.
  </p>

  <h2>Make toy storage usable by the child</h2>
  <p>
    Low open tubs can make independent pack-up easier, provided they are stable and do not create
    a trip hazard. Use broad groups rather than tiny categories: building toys, books, soft toys
    and games may be enough.
  </p>
  <p>
    Rotate toys if the available storage is overflowing. Large collections behind heavy lids or
    deep in a cabinet usually return to the floor because the pack-away step is too difficult.
    Secure furniture where its instructions require it and keep climbable arrangements in mind.
  </p>

  <h2>Give pet items a boundary</h2>
  <p>
    If the pet spends time in the living room, a bed, washable throw and small toy basket may
    legitimately belong there. Keep food, grooming supplies and the full collection of toys in
    their task zones rather than spreading them across the room.
  </p>
  <p>
    Washable materials and a clear route around beds help people and pets share the floor. The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/pet-essentials-for-australian-homes/">pet essentials guide</a>{" "}
    covers feeding, resting, entry and cleaning zones throughout the house.
  </p>

  <h2>Use shelves for display and a small amount of storage</h2>
  <p>
    Open shelving can hold books, plants and a few boxes without the visual weight of a large
    cabinet. It can also become a wall of unrelated objects. Leave some space, group items with
    intention and avoid storing heavy or frequently handled objects at awkward heights.
  </p>
  <p>
    Check the wall, fixings, load rating and rental conditions before installing shelves. Keep
    cords, lamps and power points accessible; the{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-lighting-ideas-for-australian-homes/">living room lighting guide</a>{" "}
    can help place lamps before shelving claims the useful wall space.
  </p>

  <h2>Keep the rug and walkway out of the storage plan</h2>
  <p>
    Storage furniture should not squeeze the passage between seats, doorways and the television.
    Mark its depth on the floor and test doors, drawers and lids in their open position. If a new
    unit forces the rug into an awkward size or makes the seating arrangement feel crowded, it is
    solving one problem by creating another.
  </p>
  <p>
    The{" "}
    <a href="/guides/living-room-rug-size-and-placement-what-to-check-before-you-buy/">living room rug guide</a>{" "}
    helps define the seating zone before furniture is added around it.
  </p>

  <h2>Stop entry clutter at the edge of the room</h2>
  <p>
    When the front door opens directly into the living room, create the smallest useful landing
    point near it. A key tray, a hook and a shoe basket may be enough. The goal is to intercept
    everyday items, not build a complete hallway where there is none.
  </p>
  <p>
    Anything that repeatedly travels further into the room needs either a better drop zone or a
    new routine. Adding another living room basket will only disguise that route temporarily.
  </p>

  <h2>Before adding another basket or cabinet</h2>
  <ul class="feature-list">
    <li>Name the repeated item or routine the storage will support.</li>
    <li>Measure the footprint with doors, drawers or lids open.</li>
    <li>Protect the main walking and seating routes.</li>
    <li>Check that children, pets and the usual cleaner can use the space safely.</li>
    <li>Remove or relocate what does not belong before increasing capacity.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    A living room does not need to look packed away at every moment. It should feel comfortable
    to use and easy to recover. When the nightly reset is short enough to happen, storage becomes
    part of the room's rhythm rather than another collection to manage.
  </p>

